# Creating Equitable Learning Environments > Self-Assessment

Now that you understand what is meant by equity and why equity matters in CS education, take a moment to reflect on your own capacity for creating equity in your classroom.

<img src="https://images.code.org/42af88bbeb8b9ee4716944f59e0964a1-image-1436486646128.jpg" width="450px" style="margin-right:45px; border-radius:10px;">

*[Climb that Tree](http://scholasticadministrator.typepad.com/thisweekineducation/2012/08/cartoons-climb-that-tree.html#.VZ8MMpNViko) comic via Scholastic Adminstrators Blog*

The [self-assessment](https://docs.google.com/a/code.org/document/d/1KIxGRW0VMHvqVZ6mER9gAv9yXpHTIZRkELqj2QypREE/edit?usp=sharing) that follows has been adapted from *Elements of Equity: Criteria for Equitable Schools*, developed by Jill Moss Greenberg and Susan Shaffer of [The Mid-Atlantic Equity Consortium](http://www.maec.org/) and highlights some of the best practices teachers can employ in their classrooms to create equity. 

> ## Reflect
[Download](https://docs.google.com/a/code.org/document/d/1KIxGRW0VMHvqVZ6mER9gAv9yXpHTIZRkELqj2QypREE/edit?usp=sharing) and print the self-assessment. Honestly rate yourself on each of the criteria/questions presented.

